Below are 12 dictionary-style definitions of common English words. The headword
being defined has been removed from each entry, so you see only the definition
text. Read them as a lexicographer would and assess how natural they are as
human-authored dictionary entries -- the kind you would find in a general
dictionary such as Merriam-Webster, the Oxford Dictionary of English, or Collins.

Please answer, concretely and with quoted evidence:

(a) OVERALL NATURALNESS. On a 1-10 scale (10 = indistinguishable from a
    professionally edited general dictionary; 1 = obviously artificial), how
    natural do these read as human-authored dictionary entries? Give one number
    and justify it.

(b) STRUCTURAL TELLS. Is there a mechanical, formulaic, or repetitive SENTENCE-
    STRUCTURE pattern running through them -- something that would tell you the
    entries follow a rigid template or were machine-generated, rather than the
    varied prose an editorial team produces? Name the specific structural
    patterns you notice (clause shape, punctuation rhythm, opening constructions,
    the way second and third clauses are appended, recurring phrase frames, etc.)
    and QUOTE concrete examples from the entries for each pattern you name.

(c) WORST AND BEST. Which specific entries read as the LEAST natural / most
    templated, and which read as the MOST natural? Quote them and say why.

(d) DISCRIMINABILITY. Could a fluent English reader reliably distinguish this set
    from a real published dictionary on the basis of sentence STRUCTURE alone
    (setting aside the actual definitional content / word choice)? Roughly what
    accuracy would you expect such a reader to achieve, and on what structural
    cue would they most rely?

Be candid and specific; do not soften the assessment. Quote liberally.

--- THE DEFINITIONS ---

1. a rounded object used in games and sports, especially one that is thrown, kicked, or struck with the hand, the foot, or an implement such as a bat or racket; hollow or solid, and sized to suit the game for which it is intended
2. to perform or undergo the first part of an action; to come into being or operation, as an event or state does at its outset
3. a stored record of the address of a document or web page, saved under a short descriptive title so that the reader may return to the material directly rather than search for it anew; in most browsers, an entry in a list kept for the purpose
4. no longer alive; having permanently ceased all vital functions. Applied alike to persons, animals, and plants
5. a domesticated carnivorous mammal of the wolf family, kept since ancient times as a companion, a guard, or a working animal; occurs in a great variety of breeds that differ widely in size and form, and is noted for its keen scent and its bark
6. a male parent; a man in relation to the child or children he has begotten, or one who has adopted a child and stands in the same relation. Also applied to a male animal in respect of its offspring
7. an embrace in which the arms are clasped about another person, given typically in affection, comfort, or greeting; by extension, any close encircling hold or pressure, as of a garment that fits tight about the body
8. to bring into existence by shaping, constructing, or combining materials; to produce or fashion by deliberate work
9. the natural recurring state of rest in which the eyes close, the muscles relax, consciousness is suspended, and the activity of the nervous system falls; distinguished from mere rest by the loss of awareness, and from unconsciousness of other kinds by the ease with which the state is broken
10. capable of being seen; perceptible by the eye, whether directly or with the aid of an instrument
11. an adult female human being, as distinguished from a girl or from a man. In general use the word implies full growth and the capacity to bear children
12. contrary to morality or to accepted standards of conduct, and hence deserving of blame or censure. Said of acts, choices, and dealings rather than of persons

